{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #359: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $a_1<a_2<\\cdots$ be an infinite sequence of integers such that $a_1=n$ and $a_{i+1}$ is the least integer which is not a sum of consecutive earlier $a_j$s. What can be said about the density of this sequence?\n\nIn particular, in the case $n=1$, can one prove that $a_k/k\\to \\infty$ and $a_k/k^{1+c}\\to 0$ for any $c>0$? Current best: Andrews conjectures\\[a_k\\sim \\frac{k\\log k}{\\log\\log k}.\\]Porubsky \\cite{Po77} proved that, for any $\\epsilon>0$, there are infinitely many $k$ such that\\[a_k < (\\log k)^\\epsilon \\frac{k\\log k}{\\log\\log k},\\]and also that if $A(x)$ counts the number of $a_i\\leq x$ then\\[\\limsup \\frac{A(x)}{\\pi(x)}\\geq \\frac{1}{\\log 2}\\]where $\\pi(x)$ counts the number of primes $\\leq x$. Prize: no. OEIS: A002048. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_8dcf62f2cdf2268b","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos359.erdos_359.variants.isGoodFor_1_asymptotic https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos359.erdos_359.variants.isGoodFor_1_asymptotic.","id":"vf_c5159d396d521f4c","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"attempted via frontier '?' (transfer_strength=n/a) -> no_progress","claimed_status":"draft","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_beb543ad0d97770a","kind":"dead_end","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[],"remaining_obligations":[],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_beb543ad0d97770a","trust":"signed"}],"activity_types":["attempt"],"attempt_count":1,"banked_attempt_count":1,"commits":[{"commit":"121807e20b06eb8148f594dfe13e440181252b0f","repository":"erdos_frontier","source_root":"sha256:210e6e1b2ca15973f38386a512f1f8fa66bbae72bb1b9acb1daf2e669ab279c7"}],"